from his crown and falling back, mouth opened, as if it were saying “good-bye” for its owner (or again, bringing to one’s mind the stale sentence: “all present bared their heads”). Yes, I remember all that, but there is one thing memory misses: the report of my shot. True, there remained in my ears a persistent singing. It clung to me and crept over me, and trembled upon my lips. Through that veil of sound, I went up to the body and, with avidity, looked.

